<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Technical and political
influences move bourses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CORPORATE results season had to contend with technical and political
influences on bourses yesterday, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT withstood its first-ever 'quadruple witching hour' covering the
multiple expiry of futures and options contracts, with effects which were
obvious to the aficionados, but not marked in blue chip share price terms.
Opening prices were clearly higher in Frankfurt, said Mr Jens Wiecking of
Merck Finck in Dusseldorf. At the close the DAX was 11.67 higher on the day,
and 0.2 per cent up on the week at 1,736.30 after gains of 3.65 and 0.1 per
cent respectively for the FAZ at 704.44.
The firmer start seemed to indicate that futures players had long positions
in the expiring March DAX future. Then, as DAX option contracts were settled
in the last few minutes, the index fell by around four points from an
earlier high of just over 1,740.
Underlying that, said Mr Wiecking, was a rise in companies which could look
forward to better earnings in the US, or export margins on the strength of
the higher dollar. In chemicals, Hoechst especially comes into this
category, and led the big three higher with a rise of DM4.30 to DM259.60.
Carmakers, favoured for similar reasons, saw BMW DM6.30 higher at DM560.80.
Among special situations, Continental, the tyremaker, had one of its
occasional days in the sun with a rise of DM8.30 to DM247.70 reflecting
improving fundamentals, the dollar and the possibility that stock is still
being accumulated with the abortive takeover approach from Pirelli still a
very recent memory.
In retailing, Asko took its gain on the week to DM100, or 13.7 per cent on
the latest, bullish projections from its management. The stock is 37 per
cent above its low for the year, and analysts are suggesting that
profit-taking is in order.
STOCKHOLM was mixed on a variety of corporate results as the Affarsvarlden
General index rose 2.0 to 1,009.7, 2.4 per cent higher on the week.
Asea B rose another SKr6 to SKr356 on Wednesday's good results from its
jointly owned operating company, ABB, and Volvo B closed SKr5 higher at
SKr411 after its Thursday report of a fourth-quarterly operating profit,
after five consecutive quarterly losses.
However, in transport, Bilspedition B dropped SKr10 to SKr43 on an 85 per
cent drop in 1991 profits.
PARIS brokers said that Sunday's French regional elections kept investors
out of the bourse. The CAC-40 index fell 2.87 to 1,919.12, down 1.4 per cent
on the week, in light turnover of about FFr1.75bn.
Liquid commodities of one sort or another seemed to be active. In oils, Esso
climbed another FFr27, or 3.7 per cent to FFr757 in 108,000 shares after
Thursday's 3.1 per cent gain on a doubled dividend. But Total fell FFr2.90
to FFr230.10 in 291,650 as it confirmed that its Hutchison unit is looking
into buying assets owned by the Italian tyremaker, Pirelli.
Perrier dipped by FFr33, or 2.1 per cent to FFr1,546 afterThursday's FFr34
gain, traders citing a report that Agnelli is not interested in a takeover
battle with Nestle for the French mineral water group. Another heavy faller
was Pernod-Ricard, down FFr26 or 1.7 per cent to FFr1,482 before next week's
results.
MILAN opened an hour later because of a visit by Prime Minister Giulio
Andreotti and moved little during the day with volume remaining light. The
Comit index shed 2.55 to 511.79, but up 0.2 per cent on the week. Turnover
was estimated at L80bn.
Pirelli gained L34 or 2.7 per cent to L1,263 on the Total report.
ZURICH closed slightly firmer, activity slowing from early hectic trade when
expiring Soffex options and futures took prices up to the day's high. The
SMI leading share index hit 1,852.9 at one point, but closed only 3.8 higher
at 1,837.1, 1,7 per cent higher on the week.
Higher profits took Nestle bearers up SFr40 to SFr9,550, and Swissair
bearers rose another SFr18 to SFr735 on news that the airline was cutting
down the executive board responsible for day-to-day business.
AMSTERDAM's CBS Tendency Index closed little changed, up 0.2 to 125.8, a
rise of 0.5 per cent over the week.
Elsevier, which reported a 10.8 per cent increase in profits after the
close, dipped Fl 1.40 to Fl 114.60, having earlier shown moderate gains.
Heineken, which has been performing strongly all week, came off Fl 1.4 to Fl
189.10 as some investors moved in to take profits.
Nedlloyd declined a further 2.35 per cent following its midweek announcement
that two institutions were converting loans into shares. It finished down Fl
1.4 to Fl 58.00.
BRUSSELS fell with the Bel-20 index ending 3.65 lower at 1,200.89, nearly 1
per cent down on the week. Turnover was BFr740m.
Clabecq, the steelmaker, fell BFr190 or 10 per cent to BFr1,660 after its
announcement on Thursday of larger than expected half-year losses.
ISTANBUL rose for the third consecutive day, although many investors
remained cautious, fearing violence ahead of today's Kurdish new year. The
75-share index advanced 67.52 to 3,990.61, an increase of 3.4 per cent on
the week.
MADRID rose slightly with the general index slipping back 0.17 to 258.38,
for a fall of 0.7 per cent over the week.
VIENNA drifted lower in thin volume, the ATX index closing down 3.81 to
1,046.46; but it was 2 per cent up on the week.
