FT  21 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Hornby hit by consumer spending fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HORNBY, the toy and sports boat manufacturer, yesterday reported a 45 per
cent fall in pre-tax profits before exceptionals, from Pounds 3.82m to
Pounds 2.09m, for the year to December 31 1991.
Last year's figures were restated following the reclassification of an
extraordinary item - Pounds 616,000 profit on disposal of land and buildings
 -as an exceptional item in accordance with the recent Accounting Standards
Board guidelines.
Although the fall in consumer spending affected both sides of the business,
Fletcher sports boats was worse hit, turning a Pounds 350,000 profit into a
Pounds 450,000 loss.
The company has appointed 100 more dealers in France and Spain to boost its
share of the European market.
Profits from toy sales, which account for the bulk of the company's turnover
of Pounds 32m (Pounds 39.5m), were only marginally down on the previous
year. The company is focusing on a new product range.
Mr Alan Cox, chief executive, said: 'This is a year for caution, not a year
for risks. We are going to concentrate on developing our existing businesses
instead of looking at further acquisitions.'
Net cash fell from Pounds 4.9m to Pounds 3.3m because a greater proportion
of sales occurred in November and December.
Earnings per share fell from 30.1p to 15.4p but the single final dividend is
unchanged at 9p.
</TEXT>
