<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Appeal Court frees Cyprus bank's assets: Overturning of
Mareva injunction likely to be welcomed by bankers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COURT ORDER freezing a bank's assets should be made only in unusual
circumstances, Sir John Donaldson, Master of the Rolls - the senior judge of
the Court of Appeal - said yesterday in a ruling likely to be welcomed by
bankers.
The so-called Mareva injunctions, named after the first case in which one
was imposed, have been widely used in recent years to avoid dissipation of
assets pending a final ruling in a court action. They are frequently imposed
on banks holding defendants' assets.
Banking business, Sir John said, was fundamentally dependent on the
maintenance of customer confidence that a bank could and would meet its
obligations.
Any order that could cause a 'run on the bank' would be inimical to the
purposes for which the jurisdiction to grant asset freezing orders existed.
Sir John made his comments when the Appeal Court lifted a Mareva injunction
freezing Pounds 38.9m of the worldwide assets of the Central Bank of
Northern Cyprus.
Such injunctions were granted in November to the administrators of Polly
Peck International, who are trying to recover about Pounds 1bn of the failed
international trading company's assets that they believe have been
misapplied by Mr Asil Nadir, the former chairman, and others.
The court was told that the administrators' current estimate was that there
would be a Pounds 190m surplus in Polly Peck after the costs of the
administration had been deducted.
In their pending action, the administrators claim from the Central Bank
Pounds 44.9m transferred to it by Industrial Bank of Kibris, a Northern
Cyprus bank controlled by Mr Nadir. They assert that the Central Bank knew,
or should have suspected, that the funds were being improperly diverted away
from Polly Peck.
Allowing an appeal by the Central Bank, Lord Justice Scott said the Mareva
injunction had already seriously interfered with its normal business and, if
maintained, would be likely to cause it irreparable harm.
Polly Peck's claim against the bank was 'no more than speculative', the
judge said, and it was not only wrong in principle, but positively unfair,
to impose an asset-freezing order interfering with a defendant's normal
course of business before any liability had been established.
The judge said the Mareva injunction was merely intended to prevent a
defendant defeating a plaintiff's chances of recovery by dissipating or
secreting away assets.
That principle made it very difficult to grant a Mareva against a bank,
which had to repay depositors in accordance with the terms on which deposits
were held.
The Central Bank's only customers were the authorised banks of Northern
Cyprus, which were required to keep 20 per cent of their foreign currency
holdings in the Central Bank to ensure their foreign currency liquidity.
There was evidence that the Central Bank's foreign currency liquidity had
been very seriously affected by the freezing order, Lord Justice Scott said.
Sir John Donaldson, who observed that it was the first case in which a
Mareva order had been sought against a bank as a defendant, said a central
or reserve bank could not continue to fulfil its proper functions under
local law if subject to an injunction on the way it transacted its business.
The appeal judges ordered that the Pounds 10.7m balance of the Pounds 44.9m
still held by the central bank in Midland Bank in London should be earmarked
in a separate account and not used other than in the normal course of
business, unless there were no other funds available in England. The central
bank must also inform Polly Peck's solicitors of any proposed use of the
Pounds 10.7m.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
