<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Reversing roles on the small screen - Ballot
Box
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Forget about political values, let's talk production values. Labour's party
election broadcast - on show at a television screen near you last night -
was another example of how this topsy-turvy election is reversing roles.
We have gasped at the audacity of the People's Party selling itself as the
home of prudence and the Tories as irresponsible spendthrifts. But that can
hardly be sustained by the two combatants' first brushes with the small
screen.
John Schlesinger's 'John Major. The Journey' offered the grainy print and
hand-held cameras of mid 1960s cine-verite. Urban grit, real people, Brixton
badinage, and yup, good old John Boy, man of the mean streets made, oh yes,
really very good indeed. It looked like it had been made on the proceeds of
a quick whip-round at the Lambeth Conservative Association. That was the
point.
Labour's Britain, on the other hand, has money to burn. We begin airborne,
shooting gracefully across snowy hilltops and swooping down over charming
schools plucked from those Beautiful Britain magazines found only in embassy
lobbies abroad.
As the Wagnerian horns of the 'It's Time for Labour' theme soar along with
us, a husky throat breaks through the Celtic twilight. 'We live in a country
rich in heritage,' it proudly insists, 'rich in natural resources and, of
course most of all, rich in people . . . '. But not rich enough under the
Tories.
Mr Kinnock's imitation of his countryman Richard Burton's more theatrical
advertising voice-overs confirms his powers of mimicry. Indeed, Hugh
Hudson's sumptuous film illustrates just how far perfectly normal people are
prepared to go to imitate a government-in-waiting.
The 'This Is Britain' tour is interrupted by a series of familiar faces,
talking optimistically about how they are going to turn the country into the
sort of place only before seen on Shell adverts. Gordon Brown, in what is
believed to be a historic first, actually smiles on camera - twice.
As we bank and wheel over polluted rivers, even the pollution looks rather
pleasant. Good pollution, made in Britain. It is all wonderful, and slightly
incredible.
When Mr Kinnock returns to take his natural place
on-camera, the viewers can hardly have raised an eyebrow at the flags
bedecking his office. The horns and violins, the patriotic pride, the hope
for a brighter future, must have left them with one thought. It is time,
time for a change, time . . . to put on the kettle.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-2058</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCTBGAFZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920320
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Major and Kinnock outline straight choices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRAIGHT choice between a party with policies to build a lasting economic
recovery and a Conservative administration offering a repeat of the old
boom-slump cycle was last night set by Mr Neil Kinnock at the heart of
Labour's campaign.
But as the two main party leaders brandished their rival agendas at
set-piece rallies, Mr John Major put Mr Kinnock's leadership alongside
Labour's tax policies as the issues at the heart of the election.
In a strong speech to his first rally of the campaign, in Manchester, he
joined a growing Conservative attack on Mr Kinnock's fitness to govern.
Without mentioning the Labour leader by name he said bluntly: 'We can't
afford to be led by people who don't know what their policy on foreign
affairs and defence is from one day to the next.'
As Labour sought to keep the focus of the campaign on the recession and
unemployment, Mr Kinnock, speaking to a rally in Birmingham, rounded on the
government's record and pledged that Labour would 'ignite' an early economic
recovery.
He said that, although the government, which had brought rising unemployment
and the fear of unemployment, would not even recognise its existence, the
British people did. 'That is why it is essential that the unemployment party
is defeated. The Tory government of recession must be replaced by a Labour
government for recovery.'
Mr Kinnock said Labour's Budget proposals would bring immediate assistance
for the economy. 'With each step we take, more orders will be won, more work
will be created, and more people will be employed.'
Responding to a day of intense Conservative attacks, he said it was not
surprising that the Tories did not want to fight on their record. 'Is it any
wonder they are spending millions on telling lies about us, instead of
telling the truth about themselves?'
Mr Major reserved his fiercest words for Labour's plans to abolish the
present ceiling on National Insurance contributions. He said that Labour's
shadow Budget would 'kick-start not the economy, but the society of class
and the philosophy of envy'.
Echoing remarks made by Mr Kinnock during the 1983 election, when the Labour
leader warned people not to grow old or fall ill if the Conservatives won,
Mr Major told his audience that if there were a Labour government: 'I warn
you not to be ambitious. I warn you not to be qualified. I warn you not to
be self-employed.'
He emphasised the harm he said Labour's policies would do to all on lower
incomes. Everyone would suffer because the housing market would collapse,
with knock-on effects for businesses such as builders, electricians,
do-it-yourself shops and garden centres.
The rally in Manchester was the first outing for the Pounds 500,000 set
devised by Imagination, a theatre set-design company for which Mr Andrew
Lloyd Webber was a creative consultant. Party officials, describing the set
as spectacular, said that it reflected Mr Major's personality.
</TEXT>
