FT  20 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Business leaders support Lib Dems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR PETER PARKER, chair-man of Evered Bardon, heads a group of 12 business
leaders who declare their support for the Liberal Democrats in a letter to
the Times today, Ivor Owen writes.
They endorse the party's proposal for an extra 1p on the basic rate of
income tax to finance investment in education, saying it is 'the necessary
pre-condition of a high-skill, high-value-added economy'.
They also emphasise that the Liberal Democrats are prepared to 'make the
necessary investment now in public works to get a very sluggish economy
moving again'.
The letter states: 'After 40 years which have seen Britain's relative
decline as a major industrial power continue under both Conservative and
socialist governments, rational businessmen are bound to ask themselves
whether there is not a better way forward.'
The signatories include Mr Terry Maher, chairman of Pentos, the publisher,
Lord Ezra, former chairman of the National Coal Board and a Liberal Democrat
spokesman in the Lords, and Mr Peter Boizot, chairman and managing director
of Pizza Express.
