<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Thatcher warns on borrowing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Margaret Thatcher last night gave a stern warning of the consequences of
imprudent government borrowing as she urged voters to support Mr John
Major's Conservatives in order to prevent Labour undoing the policies of the
past 13 years.
In a robust address to the Finchley faithful, the former prime minister all
but disregarded the 54,000 words of manifesto pledges unveiled by the
leading parties this week - 29,000 of which were produced by the
Conservatives.
These were 'so detailed' it was difficult to see the broader general issues,
she said. But broader issues were the ones that mattered.
In a lengthy passage dedicated to the importance of 'sound finance', Mrs
Thatcher - who is known to be privately dismayed by the sharp increase in
government borrowing - argued that this was crucial to a country's standing
overseas.
'People won't listen to you unless you demonstrate you can handle the
economic affairs and finances of your country,' she said in remarks
presumably intended to reach the ears of Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor.
What sound finance meant was 'living within your means'.
Using the plain language for which she was renowned when in office, she said
that one consequence of this was 'having to say no to some public
expenditure if it takes you over your top limit.
'Believe you me, no is a very useful word in government. It keeps your
finances sound so that we were able actually to reduce our debt.'
Mrs Thatcher's wide-ranging speech returned to the theme of Europe, which
loomed so large in her downfall, haranguing 'socialist Delors' social
charter' and warning against the consequences of a single European currency.
She urged voters not to settle for a hung parliament. 'Coalitions are not
decisive; majorities are, have been and will continue to be.'
On a personal note, she said it was 'very strange' not to be addressing her
largely elderly audience as a parliamentary candidate and that it was 'quite
a wrench' to stand down.
The meeting was convened to adopt Mr Hartley Booth, a former special adviser
at Number 10, as her successor in the constituency.
</TEXT>
