<DOCNO>FT921-2073</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCTBGAFKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920320
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Parties clash on nationalisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR ACTED last night to quash Tory attacks over its plans for the water
and electricity companies by ruling out claims that majority shareholdings
in the utilities would be bought in the short term.
However, party officials refused to deny categorically that the British
National Grid and the water companies could be nationalised in the longer
term if they failed to take consumer and environmental interests adequately
into account.
Instead of buying majority stakes in the companies, a Labour government
would introduce legislation to regulate both sectors. These would give it
powers to control prices and environmental practices.
The dispute over Labour nationalisation plans came after Mr Chris Patten,
Tory chairman, seized on remarks by Mr Roy Hattersley on BBC radio to
describe Labour's policy as 'a shambles'. The Labour deputy leader had said
his party would, 'when the time comes', buy back water shares at
'appropriate value.'
His words were quickly denied by Mr Neil Kinnock, who stated definitively
that Labour would not use public money to buy water shares.
Yesterday Mr Jack Cunningham, Labour's campaign co-ordinator, again
confirmed the leader's position.
But in a letter to Mr Kinnock distributed to the press, Mr Patten accused
the Labour leadership of being at odds with its manifesto, which talks of
public control of water being 'a priority'.
His attack came as Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, challenged the ability
of Labour's shadow Budget to fund spending commitments into the 1993-94
fiscal year.
He said that Mr John Smith's calculations depended on privatisation proceeds
that would only be available to a government ready to continue with
privatisation programmes.
Labour officials countered, however, that the government's planning for a
second tax year were based on incomplete figures.
</TEXT>
