FT  20 MAR 92 / Opera house asks consultant to investigate costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Opera House, Covent Garden, has called in a management consultant
to examine administration, production costs, and backstage operations. It
hopes the findings will strengthen its case for a big increase in Arts
Council subsidy.
'We deserve an uplift in funding,' Mr Jeremy Isaacs, director-general of
Covent Garden, said yesterday. 'We hope that this investigation will provide
the material which justifies an uplift.'
The consultant, Mr Ian Beesley from Price Waterhouse, conducted a similar
exercise at Covent Garden's rival, English National Opera. Mr Beesley will
report by September.
Covent Garden will receive Pounds 18.95m from the council in 1992-93, a 6.5
per cent increase on last year. This will make it by far the largest
beneficiary of the council.
Covent Garden operations are also being examined by a panel appointed by the
Arts Council and headed by Lady Warnock. This review is part of the regular
assessment of council clients.
The council says it is happy for Covent Garden to undertake its own audit
and will take the findings into account when making its judgment.
The Royal Opera House feels under threat. To reduce its deficit it has been
forced to increase seat prices by more than the rate of inflation to more
than Pounds 100 for important opera productions.
However, many recent new productions have attracted tepid reviews, and
audiences are at about 80 per cent of capacity compared with 90 per cent
last season.
In contrast English National Opera is on a high. The government this week
awarded it Pounds 10.8m towards the Pounds 12.8m costs of acquiring the
freehold of the Coliseum. The remaining Pounds 2m will come from the
Foundation for Sport and the Arts, run by the pools companies. English
National Opera is also expected to announce soon a surplus for the financial
year.
Covent Garden said it was confident that an outsider's assessment of its
performance would endorse its management and confirm its case for increased
subsidy.
