<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / TUC seeks mark of service quality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Trades Union Congress will today launch a campaign calling for the
introduction of a new Quality Work Assured servicemark to highlight the
importance of good employment practices in public services.
To be awarded the servicemark, an organisation would have to show that it
was committed to 'a quality staff, providing a quality service in a quality
work environment'. This would mean good practice in staff training and
development, equal opportunities, 'decent pay and conditions', partnership
and workforce consul-tation. The scheme also aims to improve investment in
training and employee involvement in the public sector. It is an attempt to
challenge government initiatives to improve service standards, such as
compulsory competitive tendering and the Citizen's Charter. The TUC says
these result in poor working conditions, low pay and unsatisfactory service.
The servicemark would be based on the approach of quality assurance schemes
such as those of the British Standards Institution.
The plans will be discussed with experts in quality management from the
public and private sectors at a seminar in London today. Contracting out has
seriously damaged the quality of public services, according to a report
published yesterday by the Public Services Privatisation Research Unit. The
unit is funded by six unions representing employees in the public sector.
The report says that 10 per cent of contracts in the NHS and local
government are terminated early - often because of the contractors'
financial problems.
Quality Work Assured. TUC, Congress House, Great Russell Street, London WC1B
3LS. Free. Privatisation. PSPRU, 20 Grand Depot Road, London SE18 6SF.
Pounds 50 for private-sector bodies; Pounds 10 for public bodies.
