<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Rise in GPs' support for fundholding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORT for GP fund-holding has increased among family doctors since the
government introduced the controversial scheme last April, a British Medical
Association survey showed yesterday, Alan Pike writes.
The survey, the most extensive ever among family doctors, shows that most
general practitioners still oppose fund-holding. Fund-holding GPs have
budgets from which they buy hospital and other treatment on behalf of their
patients.
GPs were asked in the survey to state both their initial and present views
of fundholding. The proportion of doctors in favour has grown from 10 per
cent to nearly 20 per cent. Those opposing the scheme have declined from 76
per cent when fundholding was introduced to 62 per cent now.
The survey suggests, however, that there are mixed attitudes about
fundholding even among doctors using it. Thirty per cent of GPs who are
fundholders, or are considering joining the scheme, remain opposed to the
idea.
The survey also shows that 73 per cent of GPs would like to opt out of their
24-hour responsibility for patients. They would like this to be replaced
with alternative arrangements such as the provision of out-of-hours care by
local primary-care emergency centres.
The survey will form the basis of future negotiations between the BMA and
the Department of Health.
</TEXT>
