FT  20 MAR 92 / Court rules in satellite TV wrangle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Court of Appeal yesterday ended a legal wrangle between British Sky
Broadcasting, the satellite television network in which Pearson, publisher
of the Financial Times, has a stake, and Tatung UK, a manufacturer of
satellite receiving equipment, Gary Mead writes.
The court ruled that BSkyB had no agreement with Tatung that its D-Mac
satellite receivers would be the preferred technology.
The case stems from November 1990, when two rival satellite television
companies, British Satellite Broadcasting (BSB) and Sky Television, merged
to form BSkyB. The former BSB was compatible with Tatung's D-Mac receivers,
but after the merger the alternative system used by Sky took over.
Yesterday's case will have a bearing on similar actions pending against
BSkyB by three other electronics manufacturers, Nokia, Philips and Ferguson.
Tatung was refused leave to appeal to the Lords.
