<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Lending by banks and building societies falls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LENDING by banks and building societies to the private and corporate sectors
fell sharply last month. The fall was a further sign that the recession is
continuing.
Lending by banks and building societies, known as M4 lending, rose by only
Pounds 400m, confounding City expectations of a monthly rise of Pounds
2.5bn. The slight increase brought annual credit growth to 5 per cent - the
lowest annual growth rate since 1967. In February last year annual credit
growth stood at 13.9 per cent.
The figures from the Bank of England contrasted strongly, however, with
separate data from the British Bankers Association. These showed that
lending by the nine big high- street banking groups to the private sector
(about 70 per cent of total bank lending) grew by Pounds 1.5bn in February
compared with a rise of only Pounds 400m in January.
Lord Inchyra, secretary-general of the association, warned against reading
too much into its figure. 'Looking at longer-term trends, one should
probably say no more than that the sharp decline in bank lending does appear
to have bottomed out,' he said.
Mr Chris Dillow, UK economist at Nomura Research, said the difference in
figures could be explained by a collapse in building society lending, which
is not included in the association's figures. But it was more likely to be
the result of a fall in lending by overseas banks.
Other measures of money supply from the Bank also pointed towards a stagnant
economy. Narrow money (M0), which mostly comprises notes and coins and
indicates underlying demand pressures, grew by a seasonally adjusted 2.2 per
cent in the 12 months to February. Between January and February M0 grew by
0.2 per cent.
Broad money (M4) - notes and coins plus sterling deposits at banks and
building societies - grew by 6 per cent in the 12 months to February.
This followed growth of 6.2 per cent in the year to January. In February M4
grew by 0.5 per cent.
</TEXT>
