FT  20 MAR 92 / Scandinavian hub is planned for Gatwick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREE partner airlines in the Scandinavian NRT Nordisk travel group plan
to expand their operations to turn Gatwick into an international hub for
Scandinavian air traffic in competition with Copenhagen, Paul Betts writes.
The three carriers, Transwede Airways, Norway Airlines and Sterling, are
developing new scheduled air services between Scandinavia and Gatwick to
take advantage of the deregulation of domestic air travel in Sweden.
This will enable them to compete in their domestic market against
Scandinavian Airlines System (SAS), the region's flag carrier, to develop
feeder services to London and other European cities to connect with
international networks of larger airlines.
'Domestic deregulation in Sweden this summer will enable the three carriers
to develop a domestic traffic they will be able to transport to Gatwick,' Mr
Anders Lidman, an aviation consultant to the three carriers, said in London
yesterday.
It could create a Scandinavian international hub-and-spoke system in
competition with Copenhagen, he added.
Transwede and Norway Airlines have reached several joint ticketing
agreements with international carriers at Gatwick including British Airways,
American Airlines, United Airlines and Cathay Pacific. The airlines, which
recently started scheduled services from Scandinavia to Gatwick, also
announced yesterday plans to boost frequencies to London.
Transwede, Norway Airlines and Sterling joined forces last September under
the umbrella of the NRT Nordisk travel group to compete against SAS to take
advantage of airline deregulation in Sweden and air-transport liberalisation
in Europe.
Mr Harald Rosen, Transwede's vice-president for traffic and sales, said the
three smaller airlines would compete strongly against SAS because their
costs were about 30 per cent lower than those of the Scandinavian flag
carrier.
Transwede, which started scheduled services from Stockholm to Gatwick a year
ago, had now gained nearly 30 per cent of that market, said Mr Rosen.
The expansion of NRT Nordisk's airline activities and their challenge to SAS
is expected to lead to a change in the share-ownership of the travel group.
NRT Nordisk is jointly owned by the Reso hotel and travel company and the
Wallenberg group. However, Wallenberg is also a shareholder in SAS and is
expected to withdraw from NRT Nordisk.
</TEXT>
