<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Docklands trust is withdrawn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the property company developing Canary Wharf in London's
Docklands, has withdrawn its Pounds 215m Cabot Square Trust, the largest
enterprise-zone trust yet launched.
The decision results from the impact of the general election on the Finance
Act. The shortened act omitted some provisions that extended enterprise-zone
tax relief to include occupied buildings which were crucial for the trust's
success.
Olympia &amp; York said it was 'very disappointed' that the trust could not go
ahead.
It said there was insufficient time to restructure the trust before the end
of the tax year. The transaction might be relaunched when the legislation
was enacted.
The trust, which was due to buy the Cabot Square building from Olympia &amp;
York, would have allowed investors to benefit from the tax allowances in
enterprise zones. The Pounds 30m already raised by the trust is being
returned to investors.
Independent Property Securities, the trust's promoters, had been confident
that it would have raised a substantial part of the Pounds 215m target in
the last two weeks of the tax year.
The trust's progress was hampered, however, by concern about the finances of
Olympia &amp; York, which has been forced to withdraw its commercial paper
programmes after a loss of confidence among investors.
Further controversy stemmed from the lack of detail given about the
building's valuation, which sparked an inquiry by the Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors' asset valuation committee.
It was concerned that the valuer had not considered the strength of the
developer's covenant in making the valuation.
The Cabot Square Trust was an ambitious attempt to expand the
enterprise-zone trust market, which raised a combined total of just Pounds
150m last year. It was an innovative scheme offering investors an option to
sell the building back to the developer after 10 years at a guaranteed sum
of Pounds 215m.
Property Market, Page 13
</TEXT>
