<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Financial regulation proposal divides the City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY was sharply divided yesterday over a government proposal to move
the policing of large parts of Britain's financial sector from the
Department of Trade and Industry to the Treasury.
The move, which has been driven by ministerial concern to strengthen the
regulatory framework for large financial conglomerates, was broadly welcomed
by many top City figures.
Mr Peter Rawlins, chief executive of the London Stock Exchange, welcomed the
proposal, which would bring regulation in the UK into line with other
leading financial centres.
'The securities industry is getting increasingly intertwined with the wider
banking and financial services industries,' he said. 'It would make a good
deal of sense.'
However, senior figures in the insurance industry, the only part of the
financial sector directly overseen by the DTI, were concerned about being
brought under the Treasury's wing.
The DTI - which has come under widespread criticism in recent years over its
failure to prevent a number of City scandals - is widely seen as a
sympathetic regulator of insurance companies.
Insurers fear the loss of a relationship which they believe has worked in
their favour.
The Association of British Insurers said banking and insurance regulation
'should be kept separate, so that bank depositors should not be
disadvantaged compared with insurance policy holders, and vice versa'.
The planned shake-up also raises the question of whether Lloyd's, the
troubled private insurance market which regulates itself, would be brought
under external control.
Existing self-regulatory bodies in the City also generally seemed concerned
about any upheaval in their relationship with government.
There was concern in some quarters about the overlap that would result
between the regulation of companies, which would remain at the DTI, and
other aspects of financial regulation.
'It would be a terrible muddle,' one City regulator commented. 'Who would
handle a Blue Arrow or Guinness investigation?'
The Conservative manifesto indicated this week that if re-elected, the
Conservative government would transfer to the Treasury oversight of the
financial services industry, including the Securities and Investments Board,
the chief investment watchdog, the stock exchange and insider dealing.
The proposal is also widely believed in Whitehall to cover the insurance
industry.
The City's relations with the DTI have fluctuated sharply in recent years.
Concern has been expressed about the way investment regulation was amended
under the Financial Services Act and mixed feelings surfaced over the way
deregulation in the City was handled in the 1980s.
The relationship between the Treasury and the banking sector has been
smoother as the Bank of England has acted as a buffer between the two.
Senior ministers said the proposal marked a recognition that the creation of
multipurpose financial conglomerates had blurred the previous distinctions
between banks, building societies and other businesses in the financial
services sector.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
