<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LATE buying spree helped the futures market to its first premium to the
cash market in recent sessions as traders reported a busier, but still
volatile session, writes Christopher Price
The March FT-SE contract opened up at 2,471, but was soon sold down to 2,464
before finding buyers. The contract was then squeezed higher to 2,477, its
best point of the day, with independent traders taking long positions.
Mild panic selling set in with the release of UK government statistics at
11.30am. The gilts and short sterling markets were knocked and March
followed suit, tumbling to 2,455 within five minutes.
With the opening of Wall Street in the afternoon session, the market
steadied. But buyers moved in towards the end, squeezing March to 2,471.
This was 11 higher than the previous session's close and some 2 points above
its estimated fair value premium to cash of about 4. Turnover was a busier
7,223 contracts.
The traded options market was also busier than the previous session, with
29,636 contracts traded. The FT-SE 100 option traded a third of these, while
the best-traded stock option was Asda at 3,870 contracts, followed by
British Steel and Cable and Wireless.
</TEXT>
