FT  20 MAR 92 / International Company News: Mentor Insurance creditors set
to receive first pay-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDITORS of Mentor Insurance, the collapsed Bermuda-based reinsurance
company, will receive a first dividend of 25 cents in the dollar, the joint
liquidators announced yesterday.
Nearly 800 creditors will receive payments after the end of this month,
followed by a second dividend in two or three years' time, said Mr Nigel
Hamilton and Mr Charles Kempe of Ernst &amp; Young, the joint liquidators.
The news came after approval of the arrangement by the creditors' committee
meeting in Bermuda. The first payment had been thought likely to be smaller
and come much later.
Mentor, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Ocean Drilling and Exploration Company
of New Orleans, which was set up as a captive insurance company to its
parent company, collapsed in 1985 with undiscounted gross liabilities of
Dollars 790m when it lost heavily on attempts to insure other companies. It
was wound up by the Bermuda government.
The settlement was eased by a Dollars 40m out-of-court cash payment and
withdrawal of Dollars 90m in claims by banks, announced last month following
legal action brought by the company against its parent and KPMG Peat
Marwick, its auditors.
</TEXT>
