<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / International Company News: Cariplo agrees to acquire 21%
share stake in IMI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CARIPLO, Italy's biggest savings bank, yesterday ended months of speculation
by signing a letter of intent to buy a 21 per cent stake in Istituto
Mobiliare Italiano (IMI), the big Rome-based investment banking and
financial services group.
No price for the deal, which is part of the current wide-ranging restructure
of Italian banking, has been revealed. However, S. G. Warburg, the UK
merchant bank which valued IMI for the Treasury, is thought to have put a
L6,000bn to L8,000bn price tag on the company, valuing the deal at between
L1,250bn (Dollars 1.01bn) and L1,680bn.
IMI is 50 per cent owned by the Italian Treasury, while the remainder of the
shares are held by a number of public and private-sector financial
institutions. Cariplo is controlled by a public-sector charitable
foundation.
The link between the two could provide the first step towards creating a
third big, full-service bank alongside Istituto Bancario San Paolo di Torino
and the big new bank being established in Rome via the merger of Banco di
Roma, Banco di Santo Spirito and the Rome savings bank.
However, although the Cariplo-IMI deal is appealing in business terms, it
has been criticised by some politicians as furthering the expansionist aims
of big north Italian banks, while doing nothing for their poorer southern
counterparts.
Such views have sometimes masked more complex political considerations,
linked to the some politicians' views that the Christian Democrats, Italy's
biggest party, is already over-represented in the highly-politicised
public-sector banking world. Cariplo, chaired by a former leading member of
the party, Mr Roberto Mazzotto, is firmly in the Christian Democrat camp.
The political impact of letting Cariplo, which had total assets of
L120,000bn at the end of 1990, buy into IMI will be softened by offering a
further 21 per cent stake in IMI to other savings banks over the next 15
months, with the aim of counterbalancing Cariplo's presence. The Treasury
would retain 8 per cent of IMI.
However, the proposal is still vague, and it remains to be seen whether
other savings banks will want to join in the deal. Long-running talks last
year between Cariplo and four other big city savings banks on a joint
investment in IMI foundered on political differences and hostility among the
smaller banks to paying large amounts in return for what seemed little say
in IMI.
The go-ahead for Cariplo to buy into IMI may also be the first stage in
other politically-sensitive banking transactions, notably a recapitalisation
of Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL), the Treasury-owned bank.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
