<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / International Company News: Renault's operating profit sags
as sales mark time
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RENAULT, the French state-owned car and truck maker, yesterday unveiled
profits more than double those of the previous year, although operating
earnings fell sharply in difficult market conditions.
Net profits at Renault, which has been allied with Volvo, the Swedish
automotive group for the past two years, rose to FFr3.08bn (Dollars 550m) in
1991 from FFr1.21bn. This was due to a steep drop in exceptional charges and
a fall in the interest bill, the benefits of earlier years' efforts at
trimming the workforce and paying off the group's still heavy debts.
Sales rose from FFr163.6bn to FFr165.9bn, but operating profits fell 25 per
cent from FFr6.2bn to FFr4.6bn. That represented 1.9m cars and trucks sold,
a fraction ahead of 1990, giving Renault 10 per cent of the European market,
against 9.9 per cent previously.
The fall in operating earnings was partly due to the freeze on demand caused
by the Gulf war, but also reflected the impact of last autumn's strike at
Renault's two main plants.
Sales in France fell by 14.5 per cent, bringing Renault's market share down
fractionally to 29.1 per cent, where it is still domestic leader.
Its other two main European markets, Spain and Britain, also declined
sharply. But Germany rose by 36 per cent and Renault doubled its sales
there, so lifting its German market share by nearly two points to 5.4 per
cent.
Interest charges fell from FFr1.98bn to FFr1.19m, reflecting the reduction
debt made possible by Renault's sale of FFr9bn of new equity to Volvo and
the French government, and by last year's cash-flow. Net debts fell by 43
per cent to FFr15.5bn.
The fall in exceptional charges reflects the previous year's write-offs for
Renault's subsidiary in Argentina and its truck units's US business, Mack
Trucks. There was also a one-off FFr969m gain, a payment from Chrysler
relating to a rise in Jeep sales since it bought Renault's American
interests in 1987.
Volvo contributed a small loss of FFr12m to Renault's results, though the
French group estimates that it has already saved FFr1bn on its development
bill by deciding to use Volvo's larger - more than two-litre capacity -
petrol engines.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
