<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As often as not Tomorrow's World seems like a programme for the sort of
know-all child scientist who used to irritate me at school, but two of the
subjects tonight might interest many of us. The first is a cheap method of
making high quality paper out of corn (feed it to animals when you have
finished with it) and the second is the world's first 'virtual reality'
theme park which has opened in Nottingham (7.30 BBC1).
C4's series of documentaries made by directors new to television, Short
Stories, follows two elderly members of the British Communist Party to the
43rd Congress in November 1991 where the party voted itself out of existence
(8.30).
The most famous zoo animal of all time was probably Jumbo. In my lifetime it
would be difficult to decide whether the greatest stir was caused by Brumas
(a baby polar bear of such popularity that you could buy replicas not only
in the normal soft toy material but also in soap and white chocolate), Guy
the Gorilla, or Goldie the golden eagle. All seem to me more interesting
than Chi-Chi, the sulky giant panda who became involved in the cold war and
east-west diplomacy, yet Chi-Chi is the subject of today's Arena (9.30
BBC2).
</TEXT>
