<HEADLINE>
FT  20 MAR 92 / Technology (Worth Watching): Shining example of laser's
speed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER CABLES are a bulky and expensive way of transmitting voice and data,
so in many countries telephone traffic is being switched to lightweight
optical fibres the width of a human hair.
A new type of laser light pulse generator has been developed by Pirelli, the
Italian tyres and cables group, which allows more than 80 times as much
information to be packed into fibre-optic telecommunications lines. The
pulse generator enables the capacity of fibre-optics telecommunications
links to be boosted to 600,000 telephone channels from the present 7,000.
In a fibre-optic telecommunications link, coded bursts of laser light are
fired down the line to be picked up and decoded at the other end. Pirelli's
new laser light pulse generator is able to fire bursts of light 10,000 times
shorter than current systems, allowing more signals to be packed into a
single line.
Pirelli: Italy, 2 85351.
</TEXT>
